If you can't use an external library, a simpler (but less feature-rich) approach is to implement a basic Markdown converter for a limited subset of Markdown syntax. This will be a simplified example focusing on basic conversions (headers, bold, italics, links, and paragraphs). For a comprehensive conversion, I recommend using a dedicated library.

**Simplified Markdown converter (not exhaustive):**

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::stringstream html;
    std::string inlineText;

    for (char c : markdown) {
        switch (c) {
        case '#':
            html << "<h" << markdown.find(c) <= 2 ? (3 - markdown.find(c) + 1) : 1 << ">";
            break;
        case '[':  // start of link
        case '*':  // bold or italics
            inlineText += c;
            continue;
        // Implement more cases for link extraction and formatting, bold/italics, etc.
        // ...

        default:
            if (!inlineText.empty()) {
                if (inlineText.find('*') != std::string::npos) {
                    html << (inlineText.count(*) % 2 == 1 ? "<i>" : "</i><i>" || "<b>" "</b>");
                    inlineText.clear();
                }
                // Add more handling for other inline formats
            }
            if (c != '\n' && c != ' ') html << c;  // regular text
            else if (c == '\n' && inlineText.back() != '\n') html << "<br>";  // new paragraph
            inlineText.clear();
        }
        // Handle the current character's case (e.g., finish open tags)
        // ...
    }  // switch

    return html.str();
}
```

Keep in mind that this simplified implementation will not cover all Markdown features. For a production-ready solution, it's still recommended to use a dedicated Markdown parser library.

